The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, December 29, 2003  LOOSE CHANGE
																								UTI Mutual Fund is launching six equity schemes focusing on basic industries, automobile and auto-ancillaries, mid-cap, large-cap, public sector companies and banking. The beauty of the schemes is they would disclose their intended portfolio in advance. This means you would know the stocks in which your money would be invested even before you have bought a unit. UTI Mutual Fund has applied for Sebi approval.																								At a time when fixed-income instruments are paying a pittance, Ballarpur Industries (Bilt) is borrowing at 8 per cent per annum. Bilt is offering 8.5 per cent on two-year deposits, and 9 per cent on three-year deposits. The minimum investment is Rs 15,000 and Rs 10,000 for three-year deposits under the cumulative scheme. Interest will be paid at the end of every quarter. For deposits over Rs 1 lakh, monthly interest will be paid 																								SBI Mutual Fund has introduced a scheme for non-resident Indians. The minimum investment under the scheme is Rs 50,000. Investors could choose from three portfolios  Short-term Bond, Long-term Bond and Flexi-Asset Plan. The first two would invest in corporate and government bonds, while under Flexi-Asset, investment in stocks would range between 10 and 80 per cent. Subscription closes on January 13.
